body:
The MCP servers view was leaking `DisposableStore` instances when the view was shown/hidden rapidly, particularly when toggling AI state. The disposable tracker was reporting leaked disposables with stack traces pointing to `DefaultBrowseMcpServersView.query()`.

The issue occurred because:
1. Multiple concurrent calls to `show()` could create overlapping `DisposableStore` instances
2. If `show()` was called again before a previous async `query()` completed, the intermediate `DisposableStore` would never be assigned to `this.input` and therefore never disposed
3. This created a timing-dependent leak during rapid UI state changes

The fix introduces proper serialization of query operations:

```typescript
// Before: Concurrent queries could create leaked DisposableStores
async show(query: string): Promise<IPagedModel<IWorkbenchMcpServer>> {
    if (this.input) {
        this.input.disposables.dispose();
        this.input = undefined;
    }
    this.input = await this.query(query.trim()); // Leak potential here
    // ...
}

// After: Serialized execution with proper cleanup
async show(query: string): Promise<IPagedModel<IWorkbenchMcpServer>> {
    if (this.input) {
        this.input.disposables.dispose();
        this.input = undefined;
    }

    // Wait for any previous query and dispose its result
    if (this.currentQueryPromise) {
        const result = await this.currentQueryPromise;
        result.disposables.dispose();
    }

    this.currentQueryPromise = this.query(query.trim());
    this.input = await this.currentQueryPromise;
    this.currentQueryPromise = undefined;
    // ...
}
```

Also added an explicit `dispose()` override to ensure cleanup when the view itself is disposed.

Fixes #262711.

